cure forms of work have on material and psychological well-being? This book is the first of its kind to examine the relationship between social exclusion, poverty and the labour market. It challenges long-standing and dominant myths about ‘the workless’ and ‘the poor’, by exploring close-up the lived realities of life in low-pay, no-pay Britain. Work may be ‘the best route out of poverty’ sometimes but for many people getting a job can be just a turn in the cycle of recurrent poverty – and of long-term churning between low-skilled ‘poor work’ and unemployment. Based on unique qualitative, life-history research with a 'hard-to-reach group' of younger and older people, men and women, the book shows how poverty and insecurity have now become the defining features of working life for many.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEconomic history. 0aLabor marketxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 0aMarginality, SocialzGreat BritainxHistoryy21st century. 0aPoorzGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy21st century. 0aUnemploymentxSocial aspectszGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aMacDonald, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWebster, Colin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z97831111962130 cprintz978184742910040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847429124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847429124/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles